with those noises.

718
00:38:28,560 --> 00:38:31,800
-I like the noises.
-What? You can't like
those...

719
00:38:31,840 --> 00:38:34,320
-There's a whole new set
of noises, you pillock.
-(LAUGHTER)

720
00:38:34,360 --> 00:38:35,800
-OK.
-It's the future.

721
00:38:35,840 --> 00:38:39,320
OK, let's see how fast your
elegantly entitled N ten,

722
00:38:39,360 --> 00:38:40,880
-no, NIO...
-NIO.

723
00:38:40,920 --> 00:38:42,280
-...EP9...
-Yes.

724
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:43,800
...got round, shall we?
Here we go.

725
00:38:43,840 --> 00:38:45,800
JEREMY: Top ten?
RICHARD: Come on.

726
00:38:45,840 --> 00:38:48,840
There you go.
Oh, yeah. Oh, yes, oh, yes!

727
00:38:48,880 --> 00:38:50,920
-Come on. Come on!
-(AUDIENCE GASPS)

728
00:38:50,960 --> 00:38:53,280
-Yeah!
-Yeah.

729
00:38:53,320 --> 00:38:54,440
That...

730
00:38:56,320 --> 00:38:58,160
That is faster...

731
00:38:58,200 --> 00:39:00,640
faster than
the Aston Martin Vulcan.

732
00:39:00,640 --> 00:39:02,080
You're absolutely right,
Hammond.

733
00:39:02,120 --> 00:39:04,120
It is a very impressive car.

734
00:39:04,160 --> 00:39:05,760
And it is faster
than a Vulcan.

735
00:39:05,800 --> 00:39:07,600
But it's slower

736
00:39:07,640 --> 00:39:10,280
than the petrol-powered
McLaren Senna,

737
00:39:10,320 --> 00:39:11,760
which is road legal.

738
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:13,920
-So that is petrol: one...
-Yes.

739
00:39:13,960 --> 00:39:15,680
Electricity: zero!

740
00:39:15,760 --> 00:39:17,000
All right,
don't do that face.

741
00:39:17,040 --> 00:39:18,760
Don't do that face!

742
00:39:19,880 --> 00:39:21,080
-No.
-Smug face.

743
00:39:21,120 --> 00:39:23,280
Not the smug face. I don't...

744
00:39:23,320 --> 00:39:26,920
James,
just move it on, quick.

745
00:39:26,960 --> 00:39:30,160
Yes, in this show
we are explaining
to the people of China

746
00:39:30,200 --> 00:39:32,360
that they don't need to waste
huge sums of money

747
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:35,280
on new luxury cars when they
could buy something used

748
00:39:35,320 --> 00:39:37,400
from Europe for a lot less.

749
00:39:37,440 --> 00:39:39,840
Now so far,
we've done city driving.

750
00:39:39,880 --> 00:39:41,480
We've done motorway driving.

751
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:44,080
And we've done a completely
pointless handling test

752
00:39:44,120 --> 00:39:45,800
-that Jeremy devised.
RICHARD: Yep!

753
00:39:45,840 --> 00:39:47,760
And now we had
to get to a rally stage

754
00:39:47,800 --> 00:39:49,960
to take part in another test
that he dreamt up

755
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:52,440
whilst enjoying another
night on the pneumonia.

756
00:39:52,480 --> 00:39:53,920
(LAUGHTER)

757
00:39:53,960 --> 00:39:55,480
Whatever, OK.
However, listen,

758
00:39:55,520 --> 00:39:58,360
before we left the
test centre where we did
the flamethrower -

759
00:39:58,400 --> 00:40:00,160
the flamethrower
handling test -

760
00:40:00,200 --> 00:40:04,520
we popped next door
to something called the
Zunyi Conference centre.

761
00:40:07,680 --> 00:40:11,400
It was on this very spot,
in 1935,

762
00:40:11,440 --> 00:40:14,200
that Chairman Mao
unveiled the plans

763
00:40:14,280 --> 00:40:16,480
for the future
of his country.

764
00:40:18,680 --> 00:40:22,600
This then is the birthplace
of Communism in China,

765
00:40:22,640 --> 00:40:26,960
and today it stands
as an anti-Capitalist shrine.

766
00:40:30,200 --> 00:40:33,520
Naturally we headed
straight for the gift shop.

767
00:40:33,560 --> 00:40:36,160
-(CASH REGISTER BEEPING)
-Oh, that is exquisite.

768
00:40:36,200 --> 00:40:38,680
Yes, I'll definitely have
a Chairman Mao snow globe.

769
00:40:40,920 --> 00:40:42,480
RICHARD: That one.

770
00:40:42,520 --> 00:40:44,000
-Oh, look.
-(WOMAN GIGGLES)

771
00:40:44,040 --> 00:40:46,080
How much are these?

772
00:40:46,120 --> 00:40:47,400
(CASH REGISTER BEEPS)

773
00:40:47,440 --> 00:40:50,080
So that's 230.

774
00:40:50,120 --> 00:40:52,160
JEREMY: It's Donald Trump.

775
00:40:52,200 --> 00:40:54,760
-I'm absolutely starving.
-Yeah, me too.

776
00:40:54,800 --> 00:40:57,600
-Oh, that's handy.
-That'll do.

777
00:40:57,640 --> 00:41:01,160
Having paid our respects
to Communism...

778
00:41:01,200 --> 00:41:05,360
...we got back on the road
in our fire-damaged cars

779
00:41:05,400 --> 00:41:10,480
with James still moaning
about his temperature issues.

780
00:41:10,520 --> 00:41:13,480
The air conditioning
is now so broken
that it's permanently hot,

781
00:41:13,520 --> 00:41:18,160
even when I turn it to low
and press every auto button.

782
00:41:18,160 --> 00:41:21,480
I decided there was only one
thing I could do about this.

783
00:41:21,520 --> 00:41:22,520
Ignore him.

784
00:41:23,640 --> 00:41:24,840
Jesus!

785
00:41:24,880 --> 00:41:26,560
Look at that.

786
00:41:26,600 --> 00:41:28,360
They're actually building
another motorway

787
00:41:28,400 --> 00:41:29,960
with viaducts and tunnels

788
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:32,840
on the other side
of the valley.

789
00:41:32,880 --> 00:41:36,520
You've got one motorway.
Why would you need
another one over there?

790
00:41:36,560 --> 00:41:39,400
Still, all these motorways
did mean we could prove

791
00:41:39,440 --> 00:41:43,760
that our cars work well,
as long-distance cruisers.

792
00:41:45,160 --> 00:41:47,760
If you gloss over
the slightly worn,

793
00:41:47,800 --> 00:41:50,160
interior trim on this car,

794
00:41:50,160 --> 00:41:52,840
I am staggered
at how comfortable it is.

795
00:41:52,880 --> 00:41:55,280
Every inch the Cadillac.

796
00:41:55,320 --> 00:42:00,360
It's fitted with something
called continuously variable
road-sensing suspension.

797
00:42:00,400 --> 00:42:02,200
Or suspension.

798
00:42:03,320 --> 00:42:05,560
And there's more.

799
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:07,640
In Britain,
this car was described as

800
00:42:07,640 --> 00:42:09,640
astonishingly reliable.

801
00:42:09,680 --> 00:42:13,160
Not my words,
the words of the RAC.

802
00:42:13,200 --> 00:42:15,360
The Royal Automobile Club.

803
00:42:15,400 --> 00:42:18,680
The Queen herself
as good as commended

804
00:42:18,760 --> 00:42:22,560
this car's reliability.

805
00:42:22,600 --> 00:42:24,880
RICHARD: Meanwhile,
in the stuck record.

806
00:42:26,040 --> 00:42:28,200
Lovely engine, silky smooth.

807
00:42:28,280 --> 00:42:30,080
Seats are comfortable,

808
00:42:30,120 --> 00:42:33,040
everything works,
except the air conditioning.

809
00:42:35,080 --> 00:42:37,160
I'm running out of fuel.

810
00:42:37,200 --> 00:42:40,480
There's... That's happened
very suddenly.

811
00:42:40,520 --> 00:42:44,480
Er...This is May, how's
everyone doing for fuel?

812
00:42:44,520 --> 00:42:48,200
I have...about
a quarter of a tank.

813
00:42:48,280 --> 00:42:53,120
I'm gonna need more fuel.
The mighty North Star
has drunk it.

814
00:42:53,160 --> 00:42:57,440
JAMES: Happily,
we soon saw signs
for a service station.

815
00:42:57,480 --> 00:43:00,760
That's excellent. I was just
about to start panicking.

816
00:43:03,480 --> 00:43:04,600
Oh.

817
00:43:06,520 --> 00:43:08,640
Small problem here.

818
00:43:09,680 --> 00:43:11,120
It's not open.

819
00:43:11,160 --> 00:43:13,640
JAMES: So we drove
on to the next one.

820
00:43:14,760 --> 00:43:16,640
Oh, thank God.

821
00:43:18,520 --> 00:43:19,600
Where is it?

822
00:43:21,400 --> 00:43:22,800
Where's the fuel?

823
00:43:23,920 --> 00:43:27,320
Oh, it's not finished.

824
00:43:27,360 --> 00:43:29,640
They could even be fuel tanks
waiting to go in.

825
00:43:31,280 --> 00:43:34,120
JAMES: So, we drove on
to the next one.

826
00:43:35,160 --> 00:43:38,280
Please let this one be open.

827
00:43:38,320 --> 00:43:41,440
But that didn't have
fuel either.

828
00:43:41,480 --> 00:43:45,640
How much money are they
spending on service stations?

829
00:43:45,640 --> 00:43:48,840
Well, a lot, but they're not
earning any from them,
I can tell you that.

830
00:43:50,920 --> 00:43:55,640
The problem China has is it's
building motorways so fast

831
00:43:55,680 --> 00:43:58,680
that the people
building the service stations

832
00:43:58,720 --> 00:44:03,120
to supply the motorway with
fuel...can't keep up.

833
00:44:03,160 --> 00:44:07,400
Chaps, my fumes
are running out now.

834
00:44:07,440 --> 00:44:11,040
After passing two more
unfinished service stations,

835
00:44:11,080 --> 00:44:13,440
we finally got lucky.

836
00:44:13,480 --> 00:44:16,280
Oh, thank God.

837
00:44:16,320 --> 00:44:18,440
Ooh, that's a relief.

838
00:44:18,480 --> 00:44:21,880
JEREMY: However, our
problems weren't quite over.

839
00:44:24,360 --> 00:44:26,760
I mean,
is that petrol or diesel?

840
00:44:26,800 --> 00:44:29,040
What... What's that?

841
00:44:29,080 --> 00:44:32,160
Does green
mean petrol or diesel?

842
00:44:33,800 --> 00:44:35,360
-(JEREMY LAUGHS)
-Oooh!

843
00:44:35,400 --> 00:44:37,080
(WOMAN SPEAKS CHINESE)

844
00:44:37,120 --> 00:44:39,560
-Oh, hello.
-How do you know
which fuel is which?

845
00:44:39,600 --> 00:44:43,360
Well, we've no idea.
She just comes. This is
what she just did with mine.

846
00:44:43,400 --> 00:44:46,600
-She just put that in and
I'm going, "Is it petrol--"
-(SPEAKS CHINESE)

847
00:44:46,640 --> 00:44:50,160
She's putting it in
whatever it is.

848
00:44:50,200 --> 00:44:52,360
JEREMY: With the lucky dip
fill-up complete,

849
00:44:52,400 --> 00:44:54,760
we were ready to roll.

850
00:44:54,800 --> 00:44:58,400
However, in the
RAC-approved Cadillac...

851
00:44:58,440 --> 00:45:01,920
-(CLICK, BEEPING)
-Er...my car won't start.

852
00:45:01,960 --> 00:45:04,520
It's the battery.

853
00:45:04,560 --> 00:45:07,240
Or have you filled it up
with Ribena?

854
00:45:07,280 --> 00:45:08,520
(CAR HORN BEEPING)

855
00:45:08,560 --> 00:45:10,560
As the rest of China
was keen

856
00:45:10,600 --> 00:45:13,760
to use this one completed
service station,

857
00:45:13,800 --> 00:45:17,720
I had to push Hammond clear
of the pumps.

858
00:45:17,760 --> 00:45:22,360
JEREMY: It's not really
the message we want
to be sending out to...

859
00:45:22,400 --> 00:45:24,720
the people of China,
that our cars have broken.

860
00:45:24,760 --> 00:45:27,840
-(CAR HORN BEEPS)
-I'm doing manual labour.

861
00:45:27,880 --> 00:45:30,840
-I've found the battery.
-(BLEEP)

862
00:45:30,880 --> 00:45:32,880
(ENGINE STARTS)

863
00:45:32,920 --> 00:45:34,560
(ENGINE REVS)

864
00:45:34,600 --> 00:45:36,560
RICHARD: Success.
JAMES: Very good.

865
00:45:36,600 --> 00:45:39,720
Hammond, quite a lot
of Chinese people looking.

866
00:45:42,400 --> 00:45:44,640
Well, that's the jump leads
test done.

867
00:45:44,680 --> 00:45:46,160
We've done
the jump leads test.

868
00:45:46,200 --> 00:45:48,200
If ever we needed them,
we can do it.

869
00:45:48,240 --> 00:45:51,400
-Those Chinese-made
jump leads were excellent.
-Excellent.

870
00:45:51,440 --> 00:45:53,840
Excellent.
Not that we needed them.

871
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:56,680
RICHARD:
Back on the road,

872
00:45:56,720 --> 00:46:00,160
I was wondering
if the battery
wasn't the only issue.

873
00:46:00,200 --> 00:46:03,800
I can't understand the
German messages on the dash,

874
00:46:03,840 --> 00:46:07,200
but the engine
warning light is on.

875
00:46:07,240 --> 00:46:11,000
I'll be very disappointed
if my glorious North Star
engine lets go.

876
00:46:13,400 --> 00:46:15,080
It's not going to,
it's tough.

877
00:46:16,160 --> 00:46:18,480
It'll be fine.

878
00:46:20,280 --> 00:46:22,120
JEREMY:
In fact, we all had issues.

879
00:46:22,160 --> 00:46:26,360
Chief among which was trying
to understand the road signs.

880
00:46:27,960 --> 00:46:30,600
Don't "dring" when... What?

881
00:46:30,640 --> 00:46:33,240
Don't "drmng" when tired.
"Drmng."

882
00:46:33,280 --> 00:46:36,160
JEREMY:
Descent length surplus.

883
00:46:36,200 --> 00:46:38,800
Over-speeding prohibition.

884
00:46:38,840 --> 00:46:40,760
Don't drmng when tired,
again.

885
00:46:40,800 --> 00:46:45,120
(LAUGHING) We've got a lot
of don't drmnging when tired.

886
00:46:45,160 --> 00:46:46,960
There was another
problem too.

887
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:49,440
The roads had no drainage.

888
00:46:49,480 --> 00:46:51,760
So, even in a shower...

889
00:46:52,880 --> 00:46:55,120
JAMES: Look at that.

890
00:46:55,160 --> 00:46:59,200
The cars on the other side
are sending fountains of
water onto this one.

891
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:04,240
Whoa.

892
00:47:05,400 --> 00:47:06,480
Aquaplaning.

893
00:47:09,840 --> 00:47:12,160
Holy moley.

894
00:47:12,200 --> 00:47:15,280
That man's dropped...
His crash helmet's actually
come off his head.

895
00:47:17,720 --> 00:47:21,560
Still, at least when it got
dark, things got worse.

896
00:47:21,600 --> 00:47:22,920
(CLICKING)

897
00:47:26,080 --> 00:47:30,040
Whoa! Whoa!

898
00:47:30,080 --> 00:47:33,280
They'll give you epilepsy,
these cameras.

899
00:47:33,320 --> 00:47:35,320
Constantly being flashed.

900
00:47:39,200 --> 00:47:42,000
JEREMY: After this long
and difficult journey,

901
00:47:42,040 --> 00:47:44,840
we reached
the overnight halt...

902
00:47:44,880 --> 00:47:49,440
...where we were hoping
to unwind with some
relaxing comfort food.

903
00:47:49,480 --> 00:47:51,080
(SIZZLING AND BUBBLING)

904
00:47:52,640 --> 00:47:54,760
Holy cow, that is hot!

905
00:47:56,840 --> 00:47:58,120
How... Oh, jeez.

906
00:47:58,160 --> 00:47:59,480
RICHARD:
Oh...oh...

907
00:47:59,520 --> 00:48:02,480
-What...what...
-That's goose intestines.

908
00:48:02,520 --> 00:48:04,040
Goose intest...
Do you want some?

909
00:48:04,080 --> 00:48:07,240
I've seen more
appetising things than that

910
00:48:07,280 --> 00:48:09,160
stuck to the back of
my terrier.

911
00:48:09,200 --> 00:48:12,080
A rub... Ooh!
...rubber hosepipe...

912
00:48:12,120 --> 00:48:14,400
-Nice.
-...coated in napalm.

913
00:48:14,440 --> 00:48:16,680
(BLEEP) hell!

914
00:48:16,720 --> 00:48:20,640
As our mouths melted,
I brought up
another idea I'd had.

915
00:48:20,680 --> 00:48:25,520
We really should be in
the back of these cars,
because...

916
00:48:25,560 --> 00:48:28,560
-I agree, yeah.
-...if you're
a Chinese businessman

917
00:48:28,600 --> 00:48:31,160
you're not gonna drive a car,
a 750IL or a Cadillac,
are you?

918
00:48:31,200 --> 00:48:32,760
You're gonna be in the back.

919
00:48:32,800 --> 00:48:35,040
Actually it's more
relevant here anyway,
isn't it?

920
00:48:35,080 --> 00:48:37,400
-That's what
people care about.
-It's all they care about.

921
00:48:37,440 --> 00:48:39,080
The rear seat accommodation,
leg room.

922
00:48:39,120 --> 00:48:42,880
Now, Jaguar, Audi,
Mercedes and BMW

923
00:48:42,920 --> 00:48:44,960
all make long cars

924
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:48,920
specifically for
the Chinese market.

925
00:48:48,960 --> 00:48:51,680
So, look, why don't we...
I'm sure we could do this.

926
00:48:51,720 --> 00:48:55,040
Why don't we hire some local
chauffeurs to drive our cars

927
00:48:55,080 --> 00:48:58,000
and we'll ride in the back,
which is what we should be
doing.

928
00:48:58,040 --> 00:49:00,800
-That's a proper place
to assess them.
-Mm, that is a good idea.

929
00:49:00,840 --> 00:49:04,440
And how's this for taking it
one step further?

930
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:09,800
Why don't we, tonight,
modify our cars...

931
00:49:09,840 --> 00:49:13,080
...to make them more
relevant and luxurious

932
00:49:13,120 --> 00:49:16,000
for the Chinese
business community?

933
00:49:16,040 --> 00:49:19,200
OK, and while we're at it,

934
00:49:19,240 --> 00:49:23,840
if you two dress less like
tramps and more like
gentlemen of commerce,

935
00:49:23,880 --> 00:49:27,160
the ladies and gentlemen
of China might take us
more seriously.

936
00:49:27,200 --> 00:49:28,920
JEREMY: (MUFFLED)
So we've gotta get changed?

937
00:49:28,960 --> 00:49:30,400
-Sorry.
-Yes.

938
00:49:30,440 --> 00:49:32,960
Sorry, my whole tongue
is wrapped up in intestine.

939
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:34,920
(SIZZLING AND BUBBLING)

940
00:49:39,240 --> 00:49:41,440
JEREMY: The next morning
we reconvened

941
00:49:41,480 --> 00:49:44,320
after buying ourselves
some business suits.

942
00:49:51,440 --> 00:49:54,160
We're supposed to be
sending out a message
that we're important,

943
00:49:54,200 --> 00:49:56,680
and that people should listen
to what we have to say.

944
00:49:56,720 --> 00:49:59,320
-Now I've done that.
-I think
we are doing that well.

945
00:49:59,360 --> 00:50:01,560
No, I am.
No, you just look like

946
00:50:01,600 --> 00:50:04,480
you've got a sub-machine gun
in a violin case.

947
00:50:04,520 --> 00:50:06,840
-Have you seen James,
by the way, this morning?
-No.

948
00:50:06,880 --> 00:50:09,280
No, I haven't seen
what he's gone for,
but let's be honest...

949
00:50:09,320 --> 00:50:10,560
-Brown.
-Yes.

950
00:50:10,600 --> 00:50:12,080
BOTH: It'll be brown.

951
00:50:12,120 --> 00:50:14,560
-Nothing is more certain
than brown.
-Sombre, severe.

952
00:50:14,600 --> 00:50:17,280
-Yeah.
-It's not brown.

953
00:50:17,320 --> 00:50:19,120
That's not... Ohhh!

954
00:50:19,160 --> 00:50:22,320
JEREMY: (YELLS)
Good morning, Vietnam!

955
00:50:22,360 --> 00:50:24,520
That is bold.

956
00:50:24,560 --> 00:50:27,000
Now don't pretend
you did that on purpose.

957
00:50:27,040 --> 00:50:29,000
-Well, shall I be honest?
BOTH: Yes.

958
00:50:29,040 --> 00:50:32,880
I ordered it using
a translation app
I got for my phone.

959
00:50:32,920 --> 00:50:34,680
And you mistook
green for grey.

960
00:50:34,720 --> 00:50:36,920
I don't know if I did, or
they did, or it doesn't work,

961
00:50:36,960 --> 00:50:39,480
but I said "light, grey",

962
00:50:39,520 --> 00:50:41,520
meaning lightweight, grey.

963
00:50:41,560 --> 00:50:42,960
But I got green.

964
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:44,560
Yes, and you look ridiculous,

965
00:50:44,600 --> 00:50:47,480
and nobody's going to listen
to a word you say.

966
00:50:47,520 --> 00:50:51,560
The fact is, though,
we were all suited up.

967
00:50:51,600 --> 00:50:55,680
So it was time to get into
the back of our modified cars
and get going.

968
00:50:58,760 --> 00:51:01,520
RICHARD: What's that?
-That's one of
my modifications.

969
00:51:01,560 --> 00:51:03,680
-It's Giovanni.
-No, it's Cato.

970
00:51:03,720 --> 00:51:07,240
See, I ask him for something
and then he passes it
through the ski hatch.

971
00:51:08,680 --> 00:51:11,840
-Absolute genius.
-It's barbarous.

972
00:51:11,880 --> 00:51:16,080
Having agreed
that my manservant
was a brilliant idea,

973
00:51:16,120 --> 00:51:20,680
we introduced ourselves
to our chauffeurs
and then set off.

974
00:51:27,440 --> 00:51:30,360
My driver is
the excellent Mr Hoo.

975
00:51:30,400 --> 00:51:33,160
I wonder
if he's a doctor, actually.

976
00:51:33,200 --> 00:51:35,200
Dr Hoo is not
a particularly tall man,

977
00:51:35,240 --> 00:51:38,480
but nevertheless, the space
in the back of the S Class
is fantastic.

978
00:51:38,520 --> 00:51:40,960
I've got all this leg room,
I can adjust the seat.

979
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:43,000
I can recline myself a bit.

980
00:51:43,040 --> 00:51:45,720
I can make myself
a bit more upright.
It's quite warm.

981
00:51:45,760 --> 00:51:50,440
The air conditioning
still doesn't work. I should
actually warn Dr Hoo of that.

982
00:51:50,480 --> 00:51:55,160
Doctor, I apologise, the
air conditioning is broken.

983
00:51:55,200 --> 00:51:57,720
(TRANSLATOR APP
SPEAKS CHINESE)

984
00:52:02,720 --> 00:52:05,840
Obviously our cars were built
before Bluetooth

985
00:52:05,880 --> 00:52:09,280
and internet connectivity
had been invented.

986
00:52:09,320 --> 00:52:13,720
But that's OK, because
it means you're forced to
spend your time in the back,

987
00:52:13,760 --> 00:52:17,320
doing something interesting.

988
00:52:17,360 --> 00:52:22,120
What I'm gonna do, instead
of watching CNN drone on
about Donald Trump,

989
00:52:22,160 --> 00:52:24,200
or checking on
Nasdaq prices...

990
00:52:25,280 --> 00:52:28,320
...is er...make a model...

991
00:52:28,360 --> 00:52:33,120
a matchstick model
of the Eiffel Tower.

992
00:52:33,160 --> 00:52:35,800
My colleagues had also
decided to make the back seat

993
00:52:35,840 --> 00:52:38,800
a place of learning
and self-enrichment.

994
00:52:40,560 --> 00:52:42,480
I've said many times
on this programme

995
00:52:42,520 --> 00:52:45,320
how I can't cook anything
other than baked beans,

996
00:52:45,360 --> 00:52:47,680
but I'm gonna use
this journey,

997
00:52:47,720 --> 00:52:51,480
together with this simple
stove, this wok,
and these ingredients,

998
00:52:51,520 --> 00:52:54,440
to put that right and learn
how to make supper.

999
00:52:54,480 --> 00:52:59,280
I've got
my cookery book here.

1000
00:52:59,320 --> 00:53:02,440
Steamed razor clams with
black beans and chilli sauce.

1001
00:53:04,520 --> 00:53:08,080
JAMES: I, meanwhile,
had decided to try
my hand at painting.

1002
00:53:09,200 --> 00:53:11,200
Now this is an ideal studio

1003
00:53:11,240 --> 00:53:15,000
because I can paint the
things that I'm going to see
out of the window.

1004
00:53:15,040 --> 00:53:19,720
Sort of montage, if you like,
of typical roadside sights,

1005
00:53:19,760 --> 00:53:22,280
on a chauffeur-journey
through China.

1006
00:53:24,120 --> 00:53:25,760
Trees...

1007
00:53:25,800 --> 00:53:28,560
Trees right here, there.

1008
00:53:31,200 --> 00:53:34,000
(LIT MATCH CRACKLES)

1009
00:53:34,040 --> 00:53:35,960
Lovely, lovely.

1010
00:53:37,040 --> 00:53:38,960
(CLINKING)

1011
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:40,440
Not now, Cato.

1012
00:53:40,480 --> 00:53:43,240
I could be sitting here
now...

1013
00:53:43,280 --> 00:53:46,560
...answering pointless emails
from pointless people

1014
00:53:46,600 --> 00:53:48,840
with nothing better to do
all day.

1015
00:53:48,880 --> 00:53:50,640
Not now, Cato.

1016
00:53:50,680 --> 00:53:55,040
But, no...
I'm doing something useful,

1017
00:53:55,080 --> 00:53:57,880
something joyous,
something pleasurable.

1018
00:53:57,920 --> 00:54:01,400
(TAPPING)

1019
00:54:01,440 --> 00:54:04,280
Not now, Ca... No, Cato,
no, that's inappropriate.

1020
00:54:05,400 --> 00:54:07,320
-(SIZZLING)
-Oh, yeah.

1021
00:54:07,360 --> 00:54:08,840
Oh, yeah.

1022
00:54:10,040 --> 00:54:13,480
Watercress.
Bit of that.

1023
00:54:13,520 --> 00:54:16,600
Spend enough time on
the motorway in the back
of your luxury car

1024
00:54:16,640 --> 00:54:20,040
and you could turn yourself
into a part-time
professional chef.

1025
00:54:20,080 --> 00:54:22,680
-We could improv...
-(CLATTERING)

1026
00:54:22,720 --> 00:54:24,200
Oh.

1027
00:54:25,520 --> 00:54:27,600
JEREMY:
Meanwhile, in the BMW...

1028
00:54:27,640 --> 00:54:30,600
Cato, my suit.
My suit jacket.

1029
00:54:30,640 --> 00:54:32,360
Cato, fire extinguisher.

1030
00:54:32,400 --> 00:54:33,920
Cato, now!

1031
00:54:33,960 --> 00:54:35,920
-(WHOOSH OF
FIRE EXTINGUISHER)
-Thank you. Yeah.

1032
00:54:38,080 --> 00:54:41,160
After a few more
mostly fire-free miles,

1033
00:54:41,200 --> 00:54:43,920
we pulled over
to compare our work.

1034
00:54:46,160 --> 00:54:49,120
May we see, James May,
what you have achieved,

1035
00:54:49,160 --> 00:54:51,000
instead of doing emails?

1036
00:54:56,600 --> 00:54:57,800
Well, it's naive.

1037
00:54:57,840 --> 00:54:59,320
If I were your mum or dad,

1038
00:54:59,360 --> 00:55:00,960
I'd put that
on the fridge door

1039
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:02,360
and I'd be very proud of you.

1040
00:55:02,400 --> 00:55:04,280
This is going
on the wall at home.

1041
00:55:05,360 --> 00:55:06,560
Can we taste your soup?

1042
00:55:06,600 --> 00:55:08,560
Well,
you'll have to suck my tie.

1043
00:55:08,600 --> 00:55:10,280
That's where it all ended up.

1044
00:55:10,320 --> 00:55:13,240
Were you expanding your mind
by setting yourself on fire?

1045
00:55:13,280 --> 00:55:16,440
-Is that all you've done?
-No, no, no, no, no,
it's matches.

1046
00:55:16,480 --> 00:55:20,080
One snapped
and went into my sleeve.

1047
00:55:20,120 --> 00:55:21,800
JAMES: You've ruined
that beautiful suit.

1048
00:55:21,840 --> 00:55:23,600
-I wanna see
what you've done.
-Let's have a look.

1049
00:55:23,640 --> 00:55:24,840
I'm a bit embarrassed by it.

1050
00:55:24,880 --> 00:55:27,200
Is it... It's a burnt
wreck, isn't it?

1051
00:55:27,240 --> 00:55:28,600
It's not my best work.

1052
00:55:28,640 --> 00:55:30,600
This was gonna be
your birthday present,

1053
00:55:30,640 --> 00:55:32,760
but now you've said it's
crap you're not having it.

1054
00:55:32,800 --> 00:55:35,760
Please don't laugh.

1055
00:55:35,800 --> 00:55:38,400
Oh, right.
And you made that, did you?

1056
00:55:38,440 --> 00:55:40,880
-Really?
-In the back of your car.

1057
00:55:40,920 --> 00:55:43,680
Yeah, I know, but I...
Look... At great cost.

1058
00:55:43,720 --> 00:55:45,640
Yeah. Yeah.

1059
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:49,520
JEREMY: For the next leg
of our journey

1060
00:55:49,560 --> 00:55:52,880
we tried out
the modifications
we'd made to our cars,

1061
00:55:52,920 --> 00:55:58,040
so they'd suit the world
of modern commerce.

1062
00:55:58,080 --> 00:56:01,480
Businessmen always want
a flat bed when they're on
an aeroplane,

1063
00:56:01,520 --> 00:56:04,920
so why wouldn't you want one
if you're in your car?

1064
00:56:04,960 --> 00:56:07,520
Very simple to achieve this.

1065
00:56:07,560 --> 00:56:08,880
Recline the front seat,

1066
00:56:08,920 --> 00:56:11,720
put a mattress on it,
duvet, pillow.

1067
00:56:11,760 --> 00:56:15,480
Take off what's left of
your jacket and into bed.

1068
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:18,920
Oh, it's gone dark.
That's nice.

1069
00:56:20,800 --> 00:56:24,400
In the Cadillac, Hammond had
been a little more ambitious.

1070
00:56:29,640 --> 00:56:33,680
Name me one businessman hotel
that doesn't have a gym.

1071
00:56:33,720 --> 00:56:35,080
Exactly.

1072
00:56:35,120 --> 00:56:38,000
They all do, which is why
I've fitted my Cadillac

1073
00:56:38,040 --> 00:56:39,840
with this rowing machine.

1074
00:56:39,880 --> 00:56:43,400
So as we drive along,
I can get in shape.

1075
00:56:43,440 --> 00:56:45,960
Healthy body
means a healthy mind.

1076
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,840
-How's life in your car,
Mr Hammond?
-It's brilliant, thank you.

1077
00:56:48,880 --> 00:56:52,720
-What about you?
-Oh, I'm just nodding off.

1078
00:56:52,760 --> 00:56:55,640
You go in a tunnel, it feels
like night, it's lovely.

1079
00:56:55,680 --> 00:56:59,120
Um... Question, though.
What's... What's James done?

1080
00:56:59,160 --> 00:57:01,560
I can't see him.

1081
00:57:01,600 --> 00:57:03,680
Bit more on the coals.

1082
00:57:04,760 --> 00:57:06,680
(SIZZLING)

1083
00:57:06,720 --> 00:57:09,720
I realise this now
looks like an idiotic idea.

1084
00:57:09,760 --> 00:57:10,880
It was already
a sauna in my car,

1085
00:57:10,920 --> 00:57:12,640
so I've built a sauna in it.

1086
00:57:12,680 --> 00:57:16,400
But...let's imagine you were
in the far north of China.

1087
00:57:16,440 --> 00:57:18,200
Let's imagine
it's the winter.

1088
00:57:18,240 --> 00:57:21,680
You can get through
from the other side,
through that door,

1089
00:57:21,720 --> 00:57:23,520
-enjoy a sauna...
-(SIZZLING)

1090
00:57:23,560 --> 00:57:25,080
Go back
into your car,

1091
00:57:25,120 --> 00:57:26,560
carry on with
your oil painting.

1092
00:57:27,760 --> 00:57:29,800
Ohh. Ohh.

1093
00:57:31,520 --> 00:57:34,680
There was, however, one small
drawback to my plan.

1094
00:57:34,720 --> 00:57:38,600
My driver
couldn't see his mirrors.

1095
00:57:38,640 --> 00:57:42,480
-(HORN BEEPS)
JAMES: Whoa! Bollocks.

1096
00:57:42,520 --> 00:57:44,520
-All right, all right.
-(HORN BEEPS)

1097
00:57:44,560 --> 00:57:48,480
God, Dr Hoo's getting
a right strop on. I know,
it's steamed up. Hang on.

1098
00:57:48,520 --> 00:57:50,600
-(KNOCKING)
-All right, all right,
all right.

1099
00:57:52,680 --> 00:57:55,920
JEREMY:
Oh, that's so nice.

1100
00:57:57,000 --> 00:57:58,600
Oh, that's lovely.

1101
00:57:59,680 --> 00:58:01,600
That is lovely,
lovely, lovely.

1102
00:58:03,120 --> 00:58:04,240
Mm.

1103
00:58:06,040 --> 00:58:08,600
Not... Not yet, Cato.

1104
00:58:15,400 --> 00:58:20,560
JEREMY: The next morning,
having proved that all cars
need saunas, gyms and beds,

1105
00:58:20,600 --> 00:58:22,520
we sacked our chauffeurs

1106
00:58:22,560 --> 00:58:25,600
and headed for the location
of our final challenge.

1107
00:58:29,560 --> 00:58:32,720
However, in the USS
Norman Schwarzkopf...

1108
00:58:34,040 --> 00:58:35,960
-(BLEEP)
-Geschw Grenze?

1109
00:58:37,240 --> 00:58:38,840
What does that one mean?

1110
00:58:38,880 --> 00:58:40,640
(BLEEP)

1111
00:58:40,680 --> 00:58:42,240
It's not well.

1112
00:58:42,280 --> 00:58:43,600
(BLEEP)

1113
00:58:43,640 --> 00:58:45,280
Oh, that's another...
I don't...

1114
00:58:45,320 --> 00:58:47,320
I don't know what that
warning says either.

1115
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:53,240
-Oh, God, it's dying.
-(ENGINE KNOCKING)

1116
00:58:55,720 --> 00:58:57,640
(STEAM HISSING)

1117
00:59:03,400 --> 00:59:05,400
Oh, it's losing oil.

1118
00:59:05,440 --> 00:59:07,360
(JEREMY CHUCKLES)

1119
00:59:09,840 --> 00:59:12,600
What's happened?

1120
00:59:12,640 --> 00:59:17,120
Loads of warnings came on...
and then it lost power.

1121
00:59:17,160 --> 00:59:20,480
I made it to this off-ramp
and now it's... it died.

1122
00:59:20,520 --> 00:59:21,640
Oh, dear.

1123
00:59:21,680 --> 00:59:23,720
I'm not sure my jump leads

1124
00:59:23,760 --> 00:59:25,400
are gonna get that going,
are they?

1125
00:59:25,440 --> 00:59:26,920
-No.
-Oh, look.

1126
00:59:26,960 --> 00:59:29,120
-Oh, dear.
JAMES: That's really
gone bang, hasn't it?

1127
00:59:29,160 --> 00:59:32,480
RICHARD: There's oil
coming out everywhere.

1128
00:59:32,520 --> 00:59:34,600
Do you know the number for
the emergency services?

1129
00:59:35,320 --> 00:59:36,880
No, I don't.

1130
00:59:36,920 --> 00:59:39,120
Do you know how to say,
"My Cadillac's broken down"?

1131
00:59:39,160 --> 00:59:41,160
-Do you know
what junction you're at?
-No.

1132
00:59:41,200 --> 00:59:43,200
-Oh, dear.
-No, neither do I.

1133
00:59:43,240 --> 00:59:44,920
-Do you?
-No idea, no.

1134
00:59:44,960 --> 00:59:47,160
Come on,
we've got a long way to go.

1135
00:59:49,600 --> 00:59:54,400
Leaving the multilingual
Brummie to deal with the
Chinese breakdown services,

1136
00:59:54,440 --> 00:59:57,960
James and I got back onto
what is fast becoming...

1137
00:59:58,000 --> 00:59:59,920
...the eighth wonder
of the world:

1138
01:00:05,320 --> 01:00:07,240
China's road network.

1139
01:00:12,280 --> 01:00:16,040
In 1988, China had
no motorways at all.

1140
01:00:16,080 --> 01:00:20,800
And now, 30 years later,
it has 84,000 miles of them.

1141
01:00:20,840 --> 01:00:24,160
That's more than any other
country in the world.

1142
01:00:35,320 --> 01:00:37,480
And they're only just
getting into their stride.

1143
01:00:37,520 --> 01:00:42,800
Since 2011, they've been
building 6,000 miles of
motorway every year.

1144
01:00:43,880 --> 01:00:47,000
6,000 miles a year!

1145
01:00:47,040 --> 01:00:51,720
It beggars belief and it's
not like the terrain is easy.

1146
01:00:51,760 --> 01:00:54,520
Here, though, there ain't
no mountain high enough

1147
01:00:54,560 --> 01:00:58,240
and there ain't no valley
low enough, to stop them.

1148
01:01:01,400 --> 01:01:03,040
This bridge, for example...

1149
01:01:04,400 --> 01:01:06,960
...is 34 miles long.

1150
01:01:10,600 --> 01:01:16,400
And then there's this one,
the Duge Beipanjiang Bridge.

1151
01:01:16,440 --> 01:01:19,520
You could fit the London
Shard underneath it...

1152
01:01:20,600 --> 01:01:22,240
...twice over.

1153
01:01:31,760 --> 01:01:33,080
I'm telling you.

1154
01:01:34,160 --> 01:01:36,160
In Britain, we're doomed.

1155
01:01:36,200 --> 01:01:37,720
We're doomed.

1156
01:01:39,120 --> 01:01:41,720
We were headed, though,
for an old road,

1157
01:01:41,760 --> 01:01:46,080
to test the one thing
we hadn't tested so far.

1158
01:01:46,120 --> 01:01:50,920
And here in China, it's
the most important thing.

1159
01:01:50,960 --> 01:01:53,360
The thing is, luxury's all
very well, but in China,

1160
01:01:53,400 --> 01:01:55,960
driving is
a relatively new thing.

1161
01:01:56,000 --> 01:01:58,520
People have only been
doing it for 30 years.

1162
01:01:58,560 --> 01:02:03,040
And as is the way with all
new things, it should be fun.

1163
01:02:04,800 --> 01:02:06,760
Eventually we...

1164
01:02:06,800 --> 01:02:10,400
Well, two of us, arrived at
the location we'd selected.

1165
01:02:15,640 --> 01:02:19,200
It's known as
the 24-curve road

1166
01:02:19,240 --> 01:02:25,320
because it has
24 fun-filled curves.

1167
01:02:25,360 --> 01:02:30,280
It was built in 1935 to ferry
US military equipment
to China.

1168
01:02:32,160 --> 01:02:35,480
And it hasn't really
been maintained since.

1169
01:02:35,520 --> 01:02:38,560
So the surface is
loose and potholed.

1170
01:02:38,600 --> 01:02:41,240
And it looked like
it should be a right laugh.

1171
01:02:43,200 --> 01:02:46,360
This was actually part
of the road that led...

1172
01:02:46,400 --> 01:02:50,160
the only road that linked the
then capital of China with
India and Burma.

1173
01:02:50,200 --> 01:02:52,000
Yeah, well, before that,
all the supplies

1174
01:02:52,040 --> 01:02:54,000
that came into China
had to be flown over
the Himalayas,

1175
01:02:54,040 --> 01:02:56,040
which was incredibly
dangerous in the '30s.

1176
01:02:56,080 --> 01:02:58,240
I think the Americans
lost something like 400--

1177
01:02:58,280 --> 01:02:59,720
Sorry... Sorry to interrupt,

1178
01:02:59,760 --> 01:03:01,600
have you seen
this stupid thing?

1179
01:03:03,040 --> 01:03:05,240
Well, never mind that,
look what he's driving.

1180
01:03:05,280 --> 01:03:06,880
What, is that Hammond?

1181
01:03:06,920 --> 01:03:09,240
-I guess the Cadillac's
definitely broken, then.
-(JEREMY LAUGHS)

1182
01:03:09,280 --> 01:03:10,880
(LAUGHTER CONTINUES)

1183
01:03:10,920 --> 01:03:12,240
Nice!

1184
01:03:14,960 --> 01:03:17,480
-Check out my Fulu.
-Why have you got that?

1185
01:03:17,520 --> 01:03:20,600
Well I wasn't gonna let you
have all the fun, was I?

1186
01:03:20,640 --> 01:03:22,640
Never mind that,
why have you got it?

1187
01:03:22,680 --> 01:03:27,120
My telephone translation
device at the toll booth
worked to a degree,

1188
01:03:27,160 --> 01:03:28,600
to this extent.

1189
01:03:28,640 --> 01:03:30,480
What you...
Somebody got you a car?

1190
01:03:30,520 --> 01:03:32,040
Look, I got wheels,
three of them.

1191
01:03:32,080 --> 01:03:35,720
-What engine's it got?
